{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"68f87c67-9d68-4f99-9b9d-8eac90d6ff55","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so here's a general guide for the migration:\n\n### 1. NuGet.org Setup\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new trusted publisher, specifying your **GitHub repository**, **workflow file**, and optionally the **environment name**\n\n### 2. Workflow Changes\n\n**Remove:**\n```yaml\n- name: Push\n  run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Replace with:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    environment: nuget-publish  # optional, but recommended for protection rules\n    steps:\n      # ... build & pack steps ...\n\n      - name: Install .NET\n        uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet (trusted publishing)\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Key Differences\n| Before | After |\n|---|---|\n| `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` | OIDC token (automatic) |\n| `--api-key` flag required | No `--api-key` needed |\n| No `id-token` permission | `id-token: write` required |\n\n### 3. Cleanup\n- Delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo/org settings once the new flow is verified\n- Revoke the old API key on nuget.org\n\nThe `dotnet nuget push` CLI automatically detects the OIDC token from the GitHub Actions environment when no API key is supplied and trusted publishing is configured on nuget.org.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"650bffa8-de9e-47a8-a7d4-4cd4c2966361","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"There are no files in the repository. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key to trusted publishing (OIDC). Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":511,"requestId":"B80C:23C36A:C87252:E71D